04926nam a22007215i 9781787444089DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874440897 a10.1515/97817874440892doi  a(DE-B1597)675853  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aPOL0330002bisacsh04a968.061 aEze, Chielozona, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRace, Decolonization, and Global Citizenship in South Africa /cChielozona Eze.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2018] 1bUniversity of Rochester Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRochester Studies in African History and the Diaspora ;v7900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: New World Order, New Moral Challenges -- t1 Theorizing the Present: Sources of the New Moral Self in South Africa -- t2 Nelson Mandela and Desmond Tutu as Global Citizens -- t3 The Violence of History and the Angel of Forgiveness -- t4 The Challenges of Cosmopolitan Thinking in a Postapartheid Society -- t5 Of Xenophobia and Other Bigotries: Forging Transcultural Visions -- t6 Narrating Ubuntu: The Weight of History and the Power of Care -- tConclusion: South Africa in Search of a New Humanism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamines the importance of South Africa's peaceful transition to democracy, especially in light of Nelson Mandela's belief that cosmopolitan dreams are not only desirable but a binding duty.Nelson Mandela and Desmond Tutu left an enduring legacy of forgiveness, openness, and solidarity in South Africa. This book looks at how the country's historic transition to democracy has not only changed the negative narrative about South Africa but also provided a model for a new form of ethical participation in the world. In addition to Mandela and Tutu, this book considers South African cultural theorists, poets, and novelists such as J. M. Coetzee, Nadine Gordimer, Zakes Mda, Njabulo Ndebele, and Antjie Krog, all of whom have engaged with the struggle to overcome the legacies of apartheid and create a more humane society. Most of these figures share common cultural and moral traits with Mandela and Tutu, the most outstanding of which is their belief in the notion of global citizenship. In engaging the latter concept, this work seeks to answer the following questions: How can we understand being human in a world that is increasingly marked by hatred of others? Can Mandela's vision of his society provide us with a theory of how to live in our globalized world? This wide-ranging volume will appeal to scholars and students of history, African studies, literature, ethics, and international affairs. CHIELOZONA EZE is Professor of African literature and cultural studies at Northeastern Illinois University, Chicago, Extraordinary Professor of Englishat Stellenbosch University, and a fellow at Stellenbosch Institute for Advanced Studies, South Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCosmopolitanismzSouth Africa. 0aPostcolonialismzSouth Africa. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Globalization.2bisacsh  aAfrican Literature.  aAfrican Studies.  aApartheid.  aCitizenship.  aCosmoplitanism.  aCultural Studies.  aDemocracy.  aDesmond Tutu.  aEthics.  aGlobalization.  aInternational Affairs.  aJ.M. Coetzee.  aNadine Gordimer.  aNelson Mandela.  aPostcolonialism.  aSouth Africa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787444089?locatt=mode:legacy40u